      "dealing with a nested `OptionT` structure, but perhaps it follows from the way product is defined for `OptionT`.\n\nAnother thought: perhaps we can use the fact that for the `product` of two `OptionT`, the probability of `(a, b)` is indeed the product of the probabilities of `a` and `b`.\n\nBut to do this, we would need to carefully expand the definition of `(√ó)` for `OptionT`, or use some earlier lemma that gives this property.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can instead not assume this but instead deduce that for any pair `(a, b)`, since all `a'` have the same `probOutput`, and all `b'` do too, then `(a, b)` has `probOutput` equal to `(a', b')`.\n\nThis is perhaps the best approach:\n\n1. For `(a, b)` and `(a', b')`, we need to prove that",
      "_map_prod_mk_eq_mul, mul_comm]\n    <;>\n    simp_all [probOutput_map_prod_mk_eq_mul, mul_comm]\n    <;>\n    (try norm_num) <;>\n    (try ring_nf at * ) <;>\n    (try simp_all [probOutput_map_prod_mk_eq_mul, mul_comm]) <;>\n    (try linarith)",
      "\n    intro x y\n    simp only [prod_eq]\n    -- Since the selection is uniform, the probability of selecting any element is the same.\n    -- We use the fact that the cardinality of the product set is the product of the cardinalities.\n    have h‚āĀ : Pr[= x.1 | $ŠĶó őĪ] = Pr[= y.1 | $ŠĶó őĪ] := by\n      -- The probability of selecting x.1 is the same as selecting y.1 in őĪ.\n      have h‚āā : ‚ąÄ (x y : őĪ), Pr[= x | $ŠĶó őĪ] = Pr[= y | $ŠĶó őĪ] := by\n        intro x y\n        exact SampleableType.probOutput_selectElem_eq x y\n      exact h‚āā x.1 y.1\n    have h‚āā : Pr[= x.2 | $ŠĶó ő≤] = Pr[= y.2 | $ŠĶó ő≤] := by\n      -- The probability of selecting x.2 is the same as selecting y.2 in ő≤.\n      have h‚āÉ : ‚ąÄ (x y : ő≤), Pr[= x | $ŠĶó ő≤] = Pr[= y | $ŠĶó ő≤] := by\n        intro x y\n        exact SampleableType.probOutput_selectElem_eq x y\n      exact h‚āÉ x.2 y.2\n    -- The combined probability is the product of the probabilities in each component.\n    calc\n      Pr[= x | (¬∑, ¬∑) <$> ($ŠĶó őĪ) <*> ($ŠĶó ő≤)] = Pr[= (x.1, x.2) | (¬∑, ¬∑) <$> ($ŠĶó őĪ) <*> ($ŠĶó ő≤)] := rfl\n      _ = Pr[= x.1 | $ŠĶó őĪ] * Pr[= x.2 | $ŠĶó ő≤] := by\n        -- The probability of selecting (x.1, x.2) is the product of the probabilities in each component.\n        simp [probOutput_seq_map_prod_mk_eq_mul]\n      _ = Pr[= y.1 | $ŠĶó őĪ] * Pr[= y.2 | $ŠĶó ő≤] := by\n        -- Since the probabilities are the same, we can substitute them.\n        rw [h‚āĀ, h‚āā]\n      _ = Pr[= (y.1, y.2) | (¬∑, ¬∑) <$> ($ŠĶó őĪ) <*> ($ŠĶó ő≤)] := by\n        -- The probability of selecting (y.1, y.2) is the product of the probabilities in each component.\n        simp [probOutput_seq_map_prod_mk_eq_mul]\n      _ = Pr[= y | (¬∑, ¬∑) <$> ($ŠĶó őĪ) <*> ($ŠĶó ő≤)] := rfl\n  \n  probFailure_selectElem := by\n    -- Since both components have zero probability of failure, their product also has zero probability of failure.\n    have h‚āĀ : Pr[‚ä• | $ŠĶó őĪ] = 0 := SampleableType.probfailure_selectElem\n    have h‚āā : Pr[‚ä• | $ŠĶó ő≤] = 0 := SampleableType.probfailure_selectElem\n    calc\n      Pr[‚ä• | (¬∑, ¬∑) <$> $ŠĶó őĪ <*> $ŠĶó ő≤] = Pr[‚ä• | (¬∑, ¬∑) <$> $ŠĶó őĪ <*> $ŠĶó ő≤] := rfl\n      _ = 0 := by\n        -- Use the fact that the product of two distributions with zero failure probability has zero failure probability.\n        simp [h‚āĀ, h‚āā, probFailure_seq_map_prod_mk_eq_mul]\n        <;>\n        try simp_all [HasEvalSPMF.neverFail_iff]\n        <;>\n        try aesop",
      "\n   The probability that `(¬∑, ¬∑) <$> ($ŠĶó őĪ) <*> ($ŠĶó ő≤)` outputs `x = (a, b)` is `Pr[= a | $ŠĶó őĪ] * Pr[= b | $ŠĶó ő≤]`. \n\n   But for `SampleableType őĪ` and `Fintype őĪ`, we have `Pr[= a | $ŠĶó őĪ] = 1 / |őĪ|` (as an ENNReal).\n\n   Therefore, `Pr[= (a, b)] = 1 / (|őĪ| * |ő≤|)`.\n\n   So we need to show that for any `x y : őĪ √ó ő≤`, `Pr[= x] = Pr[= y]`.\n\n   **But to do this, we need to know that `Pr[= x] = 1 / (|őĪ| * |ő≤|)` for any `x`.**\n\n   And this is not yet in the Lean code, because we have not yet proven that `Pr[= a | $ŠĶó őĪ] = 1 / |őĪ|` for `a : őĪ`.\n\n   Actually, for `őĪ : Type` with `[Fintype őĪ]` and `[SampleableType őĪ]`, we do have `Pr[= a | $ŠĶó őĪ] = 1 / |őĪ|`, because $ŠĶó őĪ is defined to be uniform:\n   - in the `SampleableType` instance for `Fintype`, it would use `PMF.uniformOfFintype`.\n   - But perhaps we do not have this instance? \n\n   Looking back, the Lean code only provides `SampleableType` instances for `őĪ` if `Fintype őĪ`, but it seems that such an instance is not imported or included in the given code. \n\n   So we can't rely on `Pr[= a | $ŠĶó őĪ] = 1 / |őĪ|` unless we add that as an instance or prove it.\n\n   Alternatively, perhaps the `SampleableType őĪ` does not guarantee uniform sampling, and it's only the case that all probabilities are equal, but not necessarily `1 / |őĪ|`. No, because if `őĪ` has `n` elements, then",
      "alc\n      Pr[=x | (fun x1 x2 => (x1, x2)) <$> OracleComp.uniformSample őĪ inst‚úĚ¬Ļ <*> OracleComp.uniformSample ő≤ inst‚úĚ] = Pr[=x.1 | $ŠĶó őĪ] * Pr[=x.2 | $ŠĶó ő≤] := by rw [h‚āĀ]\n      _ = Pr[=y.1 | $ŠĶó őĪ] * Pr[=y.2 | $ŠĶó ő≤] := by\n        rw [h‚āÉ, h‚āĄ]\n      _ = Pr[=y | (fun x1 x2 => (x1, x2)) <$> OracleComp.uniformSample őĪ inst‚úĚ¬Ļ <*> OracleComp.uniformSample ő≤ inst‚úĚ] := by\n        rw [h‚āā]",
